{"label":"Poems Collection - 6","id":"poem-6","lockAfter":2,"list":[{"id":"home","type":"passage","label":"A House, A Home","data":{"title":"A House, A Home","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Lorriane M. Halli","text":"What is a house?\nIt's brick and stone\nand wood that's hard.\nSome window glass\nand perhaps a yard.\nIt's eaves and chimneys\nand tile floors\nand stucco and roof\nand lots of doors.\n\nWhat is a home?\nIt's loving and family\nand doing for others.\nIt's brothers and sisters\nand fathers and mothers.\nIt's unselfish acts\nand kindly sharing\nand showing your loved ones\nyou're always caring."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-home","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is a house made of?","options":"*Brick, stone, and wood\nGlass, plastic, and metal\nConcrete and steel\nNone of the above "},{"qText":"What is a home?","options":"*A place where you show your loved ones you're always caring\nA place with lots of doors\nA structure made of bricks and stones\n*A place where you do unselfish acts"},{"qText":"What is a home primarily about?","options":"Love and family, Materials and construction, Location and size, Furniture and decor"},{"qText":"Which of the following is NOT mentioned as a characteristic of a house?","options":"Unselfish acts, Tile floors, Eaves and chimneys, Lots of doors"},{"qText":"What is the difference between a house and a home?","options":"A house is a place to live, while a home is a place to love\nA house is a physical structure, while a home is a feeling\nA house is a place to live, while a home is a place to love\n*All of the above"}]}},{"id":"kite","type":"passage","label":"The Kite","data":{"title":"The Kite","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Harry Behn","text":"How bright on the blue\nIs a kite when it's new!\nWith a dive and a dip\nIt snaps its tail\nThen soars like a ship\nWith only a sail\nAs over tides\nOf wind it rides,\nClimbs to the crest\nOf a gust and pulls,\nThen seems to rest\nAs wind falls.\nWhen string goes slack\nYou wind it back\nAnd run until\nA new breeze blows\nAnd its wings fill\nAnd up it goes!\nHow bright on the blue\nIs a kite when it's new!\nBut a raggeder thing\nYou never will see\nWhen it flaps on a string\nIn the top of a tree."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-kite","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What happens when a kite dives and dips?","options":" It snaps its tail\nIt falls to the ground\nIt climbs to the crest of a gust and pulls\nIt seems to rest as wind falls "},{"qText":"What does a kite do when it reaches the crest of a gust?","options":"It climbs to the crest of a gust and pulls\nIt falls to the ground\nIt seems to rest as wind falls\nIt snaps its tail"},{"qText":"What do you do when the string of a kite goes slack?","options":" Wind it back\nLet the kite fall to the ground\nTug on the string\nCut the string"},{"qText":"What happens when a new breeze blows on a kite?","options":"It flaps in the wind\nIt falls to the ground\nIts wings fill and it goes up\nIts tail snaps"},{"qText":"What happens to a kite when it gets stuck in a tree?","options":"It flaps on the string and becomes ragged\nIt climbs higher into the tree and gets stuck\nIt falls to the ground and breaks\nIt magically frees itself and flies away"}]}},{"id":"quarrel","type":"passage","label":"The Quarrel","data":{"title":"The Quarrel","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Eleanor Farjeon","text":"I quarrelled with my brother\nI don't know what about,\nOne thing led to another\nAnd somehow we fell out.\nThe start of it was slight,\nThe end of it was strong,\nHe said he was right,\nI knew he was wrong!\n\nWe hated one another.\nThe afternoon turned black.\nThen suddenly my brother\nThumped me on the back,\nAnd said, “Oh, come along!\nWe can't go on all night —\nI was in the wrong.”\nSo he was in the right."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-quarrel","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What caused the quarrel between the speaker and their brother?","options":" The reason for the quarrel is unknown\nThe brother accused the speaker of something\nThe speaker accused the brother of something \nThey were arguing about a specific issue"},{"qText":"How did the quarrel escalate?","options":" The argument became more intense and heated\nIt remained at a steady level of tension\nIt remained a minor issue throughout\nIt quickly escalated to a physical fight"},{"qText":"Who ultimately admitted they were wrong?","options":" *The brother\nThe speaker\nBoth the speaker and brother\nNeither of them"},{"qText":"How did the quarrel end?","options":"The brother apologized and the speaker forgave them\nThey both walked away angry and didn't speak for a long time\nThe two siblings continued to argue\nThe speaker apologized and the brother forgave them"},{"qText":"What was the outcome of the quarrel?","options":"The siblings made up and moved on\nThe siblings continued to hate each other\nThe speaker admitted they were wrong and the brother was right\nThe brother admitted he was wrong and the speaker was right"}]}},{"id":"beauty","type":"passage","label":"Beauty","data":{"title":"Beauty","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"E-Yeh-Shure","text":"Beauty is seen\nIn the sunlight, \nThe trees, the birds, \nCorn growing and people working \nOr dancing for their harvest.\n\nBeauty is heard\nIn the night,\nWind sighing, rain falling, \nOr a singer chanting \nAnything in earnest.\n\nBeauty is in yourself.\nGood deeds, happy thoughts \nThat repeat themselves \nIn your dreams, \nIn your work, \nAnd even in your rest."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-beauty","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"According to the poem, where is beauty seen?","options":" In the sunlight, trees, birds, corn growing, and people working or dancing for their harvest\nIn the darkness\nIn people arguing and fighting\nIn loud, chaotic environments "},{"qText":"What is an example of beauty that can be heard?","options":"Wind sighing and rain falling\nCars honking\nDogs barking loudly\nPeople arguing"},{"qText":"According to the poem, where can beauty be found?","options":" In yourself, your work, your dreams, and your thoughts\nOnly in external objects and environments\nOnly in good deeds and happy thoughts\nOnly in dreams and rest"},{"qText":"According to the poem, where is beauty found within ourselves?","options":"In our good deeds, happy thoughts, and even in our rest\nNowhere, beauty is only external.\nIn our negative thoughts and actions\nIn our dreams only"},{"qText":"Who is the poet of this poem?","options":"*E-yeh-Shure\nHarry Behn\nLorrain M. Halls\nNone of the above"}]}},{"id":"blind","type":"passage","label":"All But Blind","data":{"title":"All But Blind","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Walter De La Mare","text":"All but blind\nIn his chambered hole\nGropes for worms\nThe four-clawed Mole.\n\nAll but blind\nIn the evening sky\nThe hooded Bat\nTwirls softly by.\n\nAll but blind\nIn the burning day\nThe Barn Owl blunders\nOn her way.\n\nAnd blind as are\nThese three to me,\nSo, blind to Someone\nI must be."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-blind","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the four-clawed creature that gropes for worms in its chambered hole?","options":"mole, bat, owl, bird"},{"qText":"Which creature is described as twirling softly in the evening sky?","options":"The hooded bat, The four-clawed mole, A bird of prey, The barn owl"},{"qText":"According to the last stanza, what is the speaker blind to?","options":"someone, animals, themselves, physical world "},{"qText":"Which animal is mentioned as blundering on her way in the burning day?","options":"The barn owl, The bat, The mole, The eagle"},{"qText":"What is the message conveyed by the poem?","options":" The speaker is blind to something important and must open their eyes to it\nAnimals that are blind have their own ways of navigating the world\nThe speaker is blind and unable to see the world around them\nThe world is a cruel place for animals that are blind"}]}},{"id":"teachers","type":"passage","label":"Where Do All the Teachers Go?","data":{"title":"Where Do All the Teachers Go?","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Peter Dixon","text":"Where do all the teachers go\nWhen it's four o'clock?\nDo they live in houses\nAnd do they wash their socks?\n\nDo they wear pyjamas\nAnd do they watch TV?\nAnd do they pick their noses\nThe same as you and me?\n\nDo they live with other people\nHave they mums and dads?\nAnd were they ever children\nAnd were they ever bad?\n\nDid they ever, never spell right\nDid they ever make mistakes?\nWere they punished in the corner\nIf they pinched the chocolate flakes?\n\nDid they ever lose their hymn books\nDid they ever leave their greens?\nDid they scribble on the desk tops\nDid they wear old dirty jeans?\n\nI'll follow one back home today\nI'll find out what they do\nThen I'll put it in a poem\nThat they can read to you."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-teachers","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the poem about?","options":"*Children's curiosity about their teachers\nTeachers and their daily routines\nTeachers childhood experiences\nNone of the above"},{"qText":"What are some of the questions the speaker asks about the teachers?","options":"Where do they live and what do they wear?\nDo they pick their noses and wash their socks?\nDid they ever make mistakes and wear old dirty jeans?\n*All of the above"},{"qText":"What does the speaker plan to do in the end?","options":"*Follow a teacher back home and find out what they do\nWrite a poem about their own experiences with teachers\nAsk the teacher to read a poem to the class\nNone of the above"},{"qText":"What is the overall tone of the poem?","options":"*Curious and playful\nSarcastic and critical\nMelancholic and reflective\nNone of the above"},{"qText":"What questions does the author ask about the teachers?","options":"Where do they go after school? Do they have families and homes? Were they ever children?\nHow do they grade papers? What do they eat for lunch? Do they have pets?\nDo they have secret superpowers? Are they aliens from another planet? Can they read minds?\nWhat subjects do they teach? Do they like their jobs? Are they happy?"}]}},{"id":"word","type":"passage","label":"The Wonderful Words","data":{"title":"The Wonderful Words","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Mary O'Neill","text":"Never let a thought shrivel and die \nFor want of a way to say it \nFor English is a wonderful game \nAnd all of you can play it \nAll that you do is match the words \nTo the brightest thoughts in your head \nSo that they come out clear and true \nAnd handsomely groomed and fed- \nFor many of the loveliest things \nHave never yet been said.\n\nWords are the food and dress of thought\nThey give it its body and swing \nAnd everyone's longing today to hear \nSome fresh and beautiful thing; \nBut only words can free a thought \nFrom its prison behind your eyes \nMay be your mind is holding now \nA marvellous new surprise!"}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-words","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the poem about?","options":" The beauty and power of words\nHow to learn English\nThe importance of speaking clearly\nThe role of language in communication "},{"qText":"According to the poem, what is the relationship between words and thoughts?","options":"Words give form and expression to thoughts\nWords are unimportant; only thoughts matter\nThoughts cannot exist without words\nWords and thoughts are equally important"},{"qText":"What is the message of the poem?","options":" Everyone has beautiful thoughts that should be expressed in words\nEveryone should learn English\nOnly professional writers can write beautiful things\nLanguage is not important; only actions matter"},{"qText":"What is the author encouraging the reader to do?","options":"Express their thoughts using words.\nKeep their thoughts to themselves.\nWrite a book.\nLearn a new language."},{"qText":"Why does the author say that everyone is longing to hear \"some fresh and beautiful thing\"?","options":"Because people are hungry for knowledge and inspiration.\nBecause people are too busy to come up with their own ideas.\nBecause people are bored with their lives and want excitement.\nBecause people are always looking for something new and interesting."}]}},{"id":"vocation","type":"passage","label":"Vocation","data":{"title":"Vocation","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Rabindranath Tagore","text":"When the gong sounds ten in the morning \nand I walk to school by our lane,\nEvery day I meet the hawker crying, \n\"Bangles, crystal bangles!\"\n\nThere is nothing to hurry him on, \nthere is no road he must take, \nno place he must go to no \ntime when he must come home.\n\nI wish I were a hawker, \nspending my day in the road, \ncrying.\"Bangles, crystal bangles!\"\n\nWhen at four in the afternoon \nI come back from the school,\nI can see through the gate of that house \nthe gardener digging the ground.\n\nHe does what he likes with his spade, \nhe soils his clothes with dust, \nnobody takes him to task, \nif he gets baked in the sun or gets wet.\n\nI wish I were a gardener digging away at the \ngarden with nobody to stop me from digging.\n\nJust as it gets dark in the evening and my\nmother sends me to bed,\nI can see through my open window the \nwatchman walking up and down.\n\nThe lane is dark and lonely, \nand the street-lamp stands like a giant \nwith one red eye in its head.\n\nThe watchman swings his lantern and walks\nwith his shadow at his side, and never once\ngoes to bed in his life.\n\nI wish I were a watchman walking the street\nall night, chasing the shadows with my\nlantern."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-vocation","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What does the hawker cry every day?","options":"Bangles, crystal bangles \nFruits, fresh fruits\nVegetables, green vegetables\nClothes, beautiful clothes "},{"qText":"What does the gardener do with his spade?","options":"Uses it to dig the ground\nGives it to the watchman to use\nTakes it home after work\nSells it to someone passing by"},{"qText":"What does the watchman do all night?","options":" Chases the shadows with his lantern\nSleeps peacefully in his bed\nWatches TV to pass the time\nReads a book to keep himself entertained"},{"qText":"What is the speaker's wish in the poem?","options":"*To be a hawker crying bangles \n*To be a watchman walking the street all night.\nTo have a house with a garden\nTo be a student like herself"},{"qText":"What does the street-lamp look like according to the poem?","options":"A giant with one red eye\nA giant with two red eyes\nA small mouse with two pink ears\nA small mouse with one pink ear"}]}},{"id":"man","type":"passage","label":"The Man Who Thinks He Can","data":{"title":"The Man Who Thinks He Can","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Walter D. Wintle","text":"If you think you are beaten, you are\nIf you think you dare not, you don't,\nIf you like to win, but you think you can't\nIt is almost certain you won't.\nIf you think you'll lose, you're lost\nFor out of the world we find,\nSuccess begins with a fellow's will\nIt's all in the state of mind.\n\nIf you think you are outclassed, you are\nYou've got to think high to rise,\nYou've got to be sure of yourself before\nYou can ever win a prize.\nLife's battles don't always go\nTo the stronger or faster man,\nBut soon or late the man who wins\nIs the man who thinks he can."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-man","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the main theme of the poem?","options":"Success is all in the mind\nSuccess is based on luck\nWinning is the only thing that matters\nLosing is inevitable"},{"qText":"According to the poem, what is the first step towards success?","options":"Willpower, Luck, Skill, Opportunity"},{"qText":"How does the poem suggest one should approach challenges?","options":"By thinking high and believing in oneself\nBy thinking low and being realistic\nBy thinking they are unbeatable\nBy thinking they are easy to overcome"},{"qText":"According to the poem, who is most likely to win life's battles?","options":"The man who thinks he can\nThe man with the most skill\nThe strongest or fastest man\nThe man with the most luck"},{"qText":"What happens if you think you are beaten?","options":" You will lose\nYou will win\nYou will get lucky\nYou will get a second chance"}]}},{"id":"team-work","type":"passage","label":"Team Work","data":{"title":"Team Work","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Edgar A. Guest","text":"It's all very well to have courage and skill\nAnd it's fine to be counted a star,\nBut the single deed with its touch of thrill\nDoesn't tell the man you are;\nFor there's no lone hand in the game we\nplay,\nWe must work to a bigger scheme,\nAnd the thing that counts in the world to-day\nIs, How do you pull with the team?\n\nThey may sound your praise and call you\ngreat,\nThey may single you out for fame,\nBut you must work with your running mate\nOr you'll never win the game;\nOh, never the work of life is done\nBy the man with a selfish dream,\nFor the battle is lost or the battle is won\nBy the spirit of the team.\n\nYou may think it fine to be praised for skill,\nBut a greater thing to do\nIs to set your mind and set your will\nOn the goal that's just in view;\nIt's helping your fellowman to score\nWhen his chances hopeless seem;\nIts forgetting self till the game is o're\nAnd fighting for the team"}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-team-work","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the main message of the poem?","options":"Working together as a team is essential for success\nWinning is everything, even if it means sacrificing your teammates\nIndividual achievement is more important than teamwork"},{"qText":"What does the author mean by \"the thing that counts in the world to-day Is, How do you pull with the team?\"","options":"The ability to work effectively as part of a team is crucial\nWinning at any cost is the only thing that matters\nIndividual skill and talent are more important than teamwork"},{"qText":"According to the poem, what is more important than individual achievement?","options":"Helping your teammates succeed\nSetting goals for yourself\nBeing recognized for your skill and talent"},{"qText":"Which line from the poem emphasizes the importance of teamwork?","options":"\"For there's no lone hand in the game we play\"\n\"But the single deed with its touch of thrill\"\n\"They may sound your praise and call you great\""},{"qText":"According to the poem, what counts in the world today?","options":"Pulling with the team.\nWorking alone to achieve greatness.\nHaving courage and skill."}]}},{"id":"railway","type":"passage","label":"From a Railway Carriage","data":{"title":"From a Railway Carriage","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Robert Louis Stevenson","text":"Faster than fairies, faster than witches,\nBridges and houses, hedges and ditches;\nAnd charging along like troops in a battle\nAll through the meadows the horses and cattle:\nAll of the sights of the hill and the plain\nFly as thick as driving rain;\nAnd ever again, in the wink of an eye,\nPainted stations whistle by.\nHere is a child who clambers and scrambles,\nAll by himself and gathering brambles;\nHere is a tramp who stands and gazes;\nAnd here is the green for stringing the daisies!\nHere is a cart runaway in the road\nLumping along with man and load;\nAnd here is a mill, and there is a river:\nEach a glimpse and gone forever!"}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-railway","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the poem describing?","options":"A train journey through the countryside\nA group of witches and fairies\nA race between horses and cattle\nA child's adventure in the forest"},{"qText":"What do the \"painted stations\" refer to?","options":"The quick passing of train stations\nArtistic depictions of train stations\nPictures of stations on the walls of the train\nStations that are painted different colors"},{"qText":"What is the tramp doing in the poem?","options":"Standing still and looking around \nWalking through the countryside\nStopping to admire the scenery\nAsking for money or food"},{"qText":"What is the green for in the poem?","options":" Picking flowers\nWalking pets\nPlaying soccer\nPlanting crops"},{"qText":"What is the overall tone of the poem?","options":"Excitement and wonder\nFear and suspense\nAnger and frustration\nSadness and regret"}]}},{"id":"tragic-story","type":"passage","label":"A Tragic Story","data":{"title":"A Tragic Story","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"William Makepeace Thackeray","text":"There lived a sage in days of yore\nAnd he a handsome pigtail wore;\nBut wondered much and sorrowed more\nBecause it hung behind him.\n\nHe mused upon this curious case,\nAnd swore he'd change the pigtail's place,\nAnd have it hanging at his face,\nNot dangling there behind him.\n\nSays he, \"The mystery I've found,—\nI'll turn me round,\"—he turned him round;\nBut still it hung behind him.\n\nThen round, and round, and out and in,\nAll day the puzzled sage did spin;\nIn vain—it mattered not a pin,—\nThe pigtail hung behind him.\n\nAnd right, and left, and round about,\nAnd up, and down, and in, and out,\nHe turned; but still the pigtail stout\nHung steadily behind him.\n\nAnd though his efforts never slack,\nAnd though he twist, and twirl, and tack,\nAlas! still faithful to his back\nThe pigtail hangs behind him."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-tragic-story","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"Who is the main character in the poem?","options":"A sage, A pigtail, A curious case, A mystery "},{"qText":"What did the sage want to do with his pigtail?","options":"Change its position to the front of his face\nBraid it\nCut it off\nDye it a different color"},{"qText":"Did the sage succeed in changing the position of his pigtail?","options":"No, Yes"},{"qText":"How did the sage feel about the pigtail hanging behind him?","options":"Sorrowful, Amused, Curious, Happy"},{"qText":"What did the sage do in his attempt to change the position of the pigtail?","options":"He twisted and turned around all day\nHe asked for someone's help\nHe ignored it and went about his day\nHe cut it off"}]}},{"id":"see","type":"passage","label":"See It Through","data":{"title":"See It Through","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Edgar Albert Guest","text":"When you're up against a trouble,\nMeet it squarely, face to face;\nLift your chin and set your shoulders,\nPlant your feet and take a brace.\nWhen it's vain to try to dodge it,\nDo the best that you can do;\nYou may fail, but you may conquer,\nSee it through!\n\nBlack may be the clouds about you\nAnd your future may seem grim,\nBut don't let your nerve desert you;\nKeep yourself in fighting trim.\nIf the worst is bound to happen,\nSpite of all that you can do,\nRunning from it will not save you,\nSee it through!\n\nEven hope may seem but futile,\nWhen with troubles you're beset,\nBut remember you are facing\nJust what other men have met.\nYou may fail, but fall still fighting;\nDon't give up, whate'er you do;\nEyes front, head high to the finish.\nSee it through!"}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-see","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the main message of the poem?","options":"To face your troubles with courage and determination\nTo give up when things get tough\nTo rely on others to help you overcome your troubles\nTo run away from your troubles"},{"qText":"What is the significance of \"lifting your chin and setting your shoulders\"?","options":" It shows confidence and readiness to face the trouble\nIt shows fear and uncertainty about the trouble\nIt shows lack of interest in the trouble\nIt shows submission to the trouble"},{"qText":"What does the phrase \"keep yourself in fighting trim\" mean?","options":"To mentally prepare for a challenge\nTo avoid any form of conflict\nTo rely on others for support\nTo physically prepare for a fight"},{"qText":"What does the author mean by \"see it through\"?","options":"To face the trouble head-on and persevere until the end\nTo give up when the going gets tough\nTo seek the help of others to overcome the trouble\nTo ignore the trouble and hope it goes away"},{"qText":"What should you do if the worst is bound to happen?","options":" Face it and do the best you can do\nGive up\nHope for the best\nRun from it to save yourself"}]}},{"id":"gold","type":"passage","label":"Nothing Gold Can Stay","data":{"title":"Nothing Gold Can Stay","type":"poem","lineGap":"5px","author":"Robert Frost ","text":"Nature's first green is gold,\nHer hardest hue to hold.\nHer early leaf's a flower;\nBut only so an hour.\nThen leaf subsides to leaf.\nSo Eden sank to grief,\nSo dawn goes down to day.\nNothing gold can stay."}},{"label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","id":"mcq-gold","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"What is the main idea of the poem \"Nothing Gold Can Stay\"?","options":"Nature's beauty is fleeting and impermanent.\nThe fall from grace of humankind is inevitable.\nThe passage of time is an unstoppable force.\nThe preciousness of life is often overlooked."},{"qText":"Which line describes the fleeting nature of early spring leaves?","options":"\"But only so an hour\"\n\"Nature's first green is gold\"\n\"Her hardest hue to hold\"\n\"Her early leaf's a flower\""},{"qText":"What does the phrase \"So Eden sank to grief\" refer to in the poem?","options":"The biblical story of Adam and Eve's expulsion from the Garden of Eden.\nThe end of a golden age in human history.\nThe loss of innocence and purity in nature.\nThe inevitability of change and decay."},{"qText":"What is the significance of the title \"Nothing Gold Can Stay\"?","options":" It emphasizes the impermanence of nature's beauty.\nIt suggests that all good things must come to an end.\nIt reflects the cyclical nature of life and death.\nIt highlights the importance of cherishing precious moments."},{"qText":"What does the poet mean when he says \"Her hardest hue to hold\"?","options":" It is difficult to maintain the beauty of the first green leaves\nThe color gold is difficult to hold onto\nNature is constantly changing and evolving\nIt is difficult to hold onto the color green in nature"}]}}]}